Overview
Overview
ONDC API contract maps various use cases to different APIs and ensures interoperability as follows:
by defining the set of attributes that need to be exchanged to establish a handshake between the LBNP (logistics buyer NP) & LSP (logistics service provider);
clearly defining the single source of truth for each attribute key and thereby establishing mutability & immutability of these keys on behalf of the participants at each end of the transaction;
This document is structured as follows:
Sample JSON payload for different pre-order & post-order APIs, for thebaseline requirements;
Transaction flows for different "enhanced" use cases;
Expected behaviour of APIs for different use cases;
All attributes, defined in this API contract, are mandatory, unless explicitly mentioned otherwise. Additionally, NPs may send optional attributes as per the swagger spechere. Participants may validate the request & response payloads, based on attributes as defined, and respond with "NACK" (along with appropriate error code as definedhere) for invalid payloads.
All participants are required to ensure full compliance with this API contract on the live ONDC network.
Signing & Verification of requests & responses
Signing & Verification of requests & responses
Key pairs, for signing & encryption, can be generated using standard libraries, such aslibsodium.
Creating key pairs:
Create key pairs, for signing (ed25519) & encryption (X25519);
Update base64 encoded public keys in registry;
Utility to generate signing key pairs and test signing & verification ishere;
Auth Header Signing:
Generate UTF-8 byte array from json payload;
Generate Blake2b hash from UTF-8 byte array;
Create base64 encoding of Blake2b hash, this becomes the digest for signing;
Sign the request, using your private signing key, and add the signature to the request authorization header, following steps documented here;
Auth Header Verification
Extract the digest from the encoded signature in the request;
Get the signing_public_key from registry using lookup (by using the ukId in the authorization header);
Create (UTF-8) byte array from theraw payloadand generate Blake2b hash;
Compare generated Blake2b hash with the decoded digest from the signature in the request;
In case of failure to verify, HTTP error 401 should be thrown;
Registry lookup
Registry lookup
Each NP will have an entry in the registry for their entity. Every participant on the ONDC registry may have 1 or more entries in the registry, with "ukid" for each such entry;
Signing & Verification of requests and responses using auth headers is definedhere;
All requests & responses have to be signed by the sender and verified by the receiver. If any request fails verification, it should be rejected (NACK) with http 401 error code;
The identity of the sender of a request is sent, through the auth header, as follows:
keyId="{subscriber_id}|{unique_key_id}|{algorithm}"
Signing by LBNP & LSP will be using their private key, for which the corresponding public key will be in the registry for their "ukid";
Verification of requests using registry /lookup usesthisAPI spec. Participants can either use the registry lookup endpoints fromhereor cache the registry locally (with refresh at regular intervals) for a local lookup.Following options are available:
/v2.0/lookup
request:
{
"subscriber_id":"bnp.com",
"domain[1]":"ONDC:RET10",
"ukId":"UKID1",
"country[2]":"IND",
"city[3]":"std:080",
"type[4]":"BPP"
}
/v2.0/lookup supports secure access using Authorization headers. Steps to create Authorization header is mentioned in2.cabove.
Sample Curl:
curl --location 'https://prod.registry.ondc.org/v2.0/lookup' \
--header 'Content-Type: application/json' \
--header 'Authorization: Signature keyId="example-bap.com|bap1234|ed25519", algorithm="ed25519", created="<timestamp>", expires="<timestamp>", headers="(created)(expires)digest", signature="<signature>"' \
--data '{
"subscriber_id":"bnp.com",
"ukId":"UKID1"
}'
response:
(will be an array with 1 or more objects, depending on whether the entity, identified by the subscriber_id, has registered as different participants in a domain, e.g. BNP, SNP)
