Construct of APIs & transaction trail
Construct of APIs & transaction trail
All APIs follow the same construct and include:
Context- includes transaction_id, message_id and other attribute keys that identify the source & destination of the message being sent through the API request or response;
Message- identifies the content of the message e.g. the search intent, catalog details, order details, etc.;
All APIs are asynchronous, i.e.:
request is sent from sender to recipient;
recipient acknowledges the request by sending an "ACK" or sends "NACK" if the recipient cannot validate the request;
recipient sends response through the callback for the corresponding request API e.g. /on_search callback for /search request;
recipient of callback (could be the original sender) acknowledges the response by sending an "ACK" or "NACK" if the recipient cannot validate the request;
Every request & response pair is identified by a transaction_id + unique message_id & the sender of a request is able to correlate the response to the request using the above;
If a stale request or response is received, i.e. with timestamp earlier than similar request or response (identified by the transaction_id + message_id) that has already been processed, the recipient can send "NACK" with the error code "65003";
Error block can be sent in sync (in response to request) or async (along with callback) mode and should have the following attribute keys: error.type, error.code;
ONDC standard error codes are definedhere;
Transaction trail for a buyer is maintained through a unique transaction_id for the pre-order stage, i.e. /search, /init, /confirm;
Unique id for an order on a network will be identified by the transaction_id & order id;
Swagger link ishere;
Version compatibility
Version compatibility
For all new features enabled from 1.2.5:
List of all "baseline" & "enhanced" features ishere;
Transaction flow for new features, with corresponding feature id, ishere;
LSPs & LBNPs may prioritize & enable one or more features as per their business requirements;
LSP & LBNP will publish the list of features enabled for mutualdiscovery;
Context.version, for the corresponding APIs, will be set to "1.2.5";
Version 1.2.5 will be considered an update to version 1.2.0, as each new feature will be incrementally layered on the base version 1.2.0;
Compatibility between 1.2.5 & 1.2.0:
Full backward compatibilitybetween lower version (1.2.0) and higher version (1.2.5) means NPs using the lower version will be able to communicate with NPs using the higher version without making any changes;
Full backward compatibility between 1.2.5 and 1.2.0 will not be possible due to the following change to the baseline features:
Updated flow for RTO;
Hence, 1.2.5 shall be considered to be side-by-side compatible with version 1.2.0;with the exception of the above feature, all other APIs will be fully backward compatiblewith 1.2.0 version of the same APIs:
LBNP sends 1.2.0 API request => some LSPs may send 1.2.0 response, other LSPs may send 1.2.5 response;
LBNP sends 1.2.5 API request => some LSPs may send 1.2.0 response, other LSPs may send 1.2.5 response;
LSP sending 1.2.5 response must also include the list of features supported;
LBNP supporting 1.2.5 features may enable business workflows for supported features based on feature discovery;
NPs may have version check enabled for "1.2.*";
